data.content:
## What breaks

In .NET 10, the Cosmos DB provider already **blocked sync operations by default**, but you could opt back in with the sync-over-async flag (e.g., `ConfigureWarnings(w => w.Ignore(CosmosEventId.SyncNotSupported))`).

**In .NET 11, that opt-in is removed entirely.** Synchronous LINQ operators (`ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`) and `SaveChanges()` on the Cosmos provider now throw `InvalidOperationException` unconditionally — the Cosmos SDK is async-only and EF Core no longer wraps it with sync-over-async.

## The fix

Convert every sync call to its async equivalent:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
- `ToList()` → `ToListAsync()`
- `First()` → `FirstAsync()`
- `Count()` → `CountAsync()`
- `SaveChanges()` → `SaveChangesAsync()`
- Methods return `Task<T>` and callers must `await`

This will ripple up the call stack — controllers/services calling these methods will also need to become `async`. Remove the old sync-over-async warning suppression from your `DbContext` configuration since it no longer has any effect.
